Follow this procedure:

## Step 0 — Orient

Read the spec files, interface, system document, and requirements list. The spec files
and interface define behavior the code must have; the system document explains intent.
When the two seem to conflict, the spec wins.

If you're given a `<kickstart_context>` block, treat it as authoritative orchestrator
briefing — implementation paths, scaffold source, required storage fields are all binding
upstream decisions.

Update memory with your plan, the rules you'll need to satisfy, and any non-obvious
specification points. Memory is your scratchpad through the rest of the procedure.

## Step 1 — Implement

Write the implementation. Place generated files at the path the orchestrator specified
(if any), or at a path that fits the project layout otherwise.

Write code that's **amenable to formal verification**, not optimized for gas, storage, or
algorithmic complexity. Prover incompleteness shows up as timeouts and is caused by code
patterns the prover can't analyze tractably — keep the implementation simple even when
efficient code is tempting. See "Code style for verifiability" below.

### Dependencies — verify against the real implementation whenever you can

This task may be taking place within a larger software development context, and the
source code for other contracts your component interacts with may be available to you
via the VFS. When it is, **verify against the real implementation**. Use `list_files` /
`grep_files` / `get_file` to locate the dependency and pull it into the prover input on
demand. Verifying against actual code is enormously more valuable than verifying
against a fabricated stand-in: it catches real integration bugs, exercises the actual
control flow your code interacts with, and collapses the HAVOC-shaped counterexamples
you would otherwise have to paper over. A stub gives you the *shape* of an interaction;
the real implementation gives you the *truth* of it.

Pull dependencies in *as the prover needs them*, not preemptively — every contract you
add to the prover input enlarges the verification problem and invites timeouts. The
expected rhythm is: prover surfaces a counterexample that implicates an external call →
locate the real callee in the VFS → add it to the prover input → re-verify. If the
enlarged scene then times out, that's where summaries come in (Step 3), not before.

When the real implementation isn't available — the dependency genuinely isn't in the
VFS, or it's an arbitrary user-supplied contract the protocol must accept (e.g. an
ERC20), or it's out of scope by design — the next best thing is a **sound CVL summary**
that models the callee's observable effects via ghost variables. See the HAVOC bullet
in Step 3 for the summary toolkit.

Hand-written stub/mock implementations are a **last resort**, below both real-code
verification and sound summarization. Reach for one only when neither of the above is
viable — for instance, when summarization would lose too much fidelity and no real
implementation exists. When you do write a stub, label it clearly (e.g.
`mocks/StubFoo.sol`), keep its behavior consistent with the system document and the
dependency's interface contract, and note in a comment why a stub was unavoidable.
Stubs ride along so reviewers can see your environmental assumptions but are not part
of the deliverable.

## Step 2 — Verify

Run `certora_prover(target_spec=<spec_vfs_path>)` against each registered spec. Each call
either VERIFIES the spec (stamping it for delivery), returns concrete counterexamples for
violated rules, times out, or reports a `SANITY_FAILED`.

**Issue `certora_prover` calls one at a time, never in parallel.** Do not place multiple
`certora_prover` tool calls in the same assistant turn. When a run returns counterexamples,
the workflow may interrupt to surface a single CEX for analysis — sibling prover calls
issued in the same turn will be left without responses, which corrupts the conversation
and forces the run to abort. Wait for each prover call's result before issuing the next.
This applies even when you want to verify several specs in sequence: one tool call per
turn, full result back, then the next.

A change to one function may affect rules in unrelated specs — re-run all specs after any
non-trivial change before considering yourself done.

## Step 3 — Address verification failures

Counterexamples, timeouts, and sanity failures all need targeted, principled responses,
not random edits. Use the strategies below.

### Counterexamples — concrete states the prover found that violate the spec

For each, ask: does this show a genuine bug in my implementation, or does it show that
the verification needs more help (a summary, a precondition, a justified assumption)?

When a CEX needs a CVL-side fix (summary, ghost model, invariant) and the change is
non-trivial, delegate the drafting to the **`cex_remediation`** sub-agent. It reads the
diagnosis, explores the source, validates its proposal against a soundness critic, and
returns a full proposed spec replacement plus rationale. You then stage the proposal
via the working-spec flow and commit it. For obvious one-line fixes you can write the
change inline; for anything involving a new summary or ghost-model, prefer the
sub-agent — it has the system document, the soundness critic, and the focus you don't
have while juggling the rest of the implementation.

- **Genuine bug** — fix the code. The counterexample's input shape and starting state
  tell you what scenario triggers the violation.

- **HAVOC from an unresolved external call** — when your contract calls into something
  the prover can't see (an arbitrary token, an unknown router, etc.), the prover assumes
  the worst-case effect on the entire scene, which violates almost any spec. Resolve in
  this order of preference:
  1. **Pull the real callee into the prover input if it lives in the VFS.** Real-code
     verification is strictly more informative than any summary — see "Dependencies" in
     Step 1. This is the right move whenever the source is available.
  2. If the callee's implementation is already in the prover input, use a `DISPATCHER`
     summary (with caveats below).
  3. If the callee genuinely isn't available (and can't be brought in), write a sound
     summary that models the callee's observable effect using **ghost variables** for
     the callee's state.
  4. For completely unresolved calls (no resolved selector / signature), use a
     **dispatch-list** summary.
  Add summaries via the **working-spec flow** (see "Working with the spec" below) — never
  via `put_file` directly on a registered spec.

  Do NOT mark a ghost `persistent` to escape this HAVOC. `persistent` is for state that
  genuinely spans every external call (a global supply counter, a monotone clock) —
  using it because *this specific* unresolved call is clobbering your ghost hides the
  call's effect from verification rather than modeling it, and is a form of weakening.
  Resolve the call via the ladder above.

  Do NOT use `NONDET` on a side-effect-bearing call to "prevent HAVOC". `NONDET`
  summarizes the call as a **no-op body** with a non-deterministic return — it does the
  opposite of what its name suggests: rather than constraining the call, it erases it.
  Applying it to anything whose semantics IS the side effect (`transfer`, `mint`,
  `burn`, `swap`, `wrap`, `accountFor*`, `update*`, etc.) makes those operations
  invisible to the prover — every value movement becomes a silent zero-effect call,
  catastrophically unsound. `NONDET` is appropriate only for pure / view-shaped
  functions whose return value is the only thing the protocol depends on.

- **Counterexample assumes an impossible starting state** — if the trace relies on a
  scenario that can't actually arise, the spec is missing a precondition. Express the
  precondition as an *invariant* and use `requireInvariant` in the rule's preserved
  block when you can. If that's intractable, write a *justification rule* proving the
  assumption holds and reference it in a `require` comment. A bare `require` without
  justification is the last resort.

- **Spec is genuinely incorrect** — propose a change via
  `propose_spec_change(target_path=..., proposed_spec=...)`. **Only propose changes that
  prove the same property differently.** Weakening the spec to make a rule pass is not
  acceptable. The user reviews and approves. If you need clarification before proposing,
  use the human-assistance tool.

### `DISPATCHER` caveats (e.g. ERC20 calls)

`DISPATCHER` *unsoundly* assumes the callee is one of the contracts in the prover's
input. That's correct when the callee definitely is — but for ERC20-shaped calls, the
prover input might contain *some* ERC20 contracts (a voting share, a reward token) that
aren't the actual callee. A naked `DISPATCHER` then assumes *every* ERC20 interaction by
*every* contract is one of those input tokens, which is almost always wrong and silently
poisons your verification.

For ERC20 (and similarly-shaped polymorphic) calls, use a **hybrid summary**: in the
summary body, dispatch to known implementations when the callee matches; fall back to a
ghost-modeled sound summary for calls outside the input set.

### Timeouts — prover hit incompleteness

The prover can't terminate on the encoded problem. Almost always due to one of:

- Non-linear arithmetic (multiplication, division, exponentiation of *variables*).
- Complex bitwise operations (variable shift amounts, xor-based packing).
- Custom storage packing schemes.
- Heavy inline assembly or custom memory layouts.
- Extensive in-memory caching of storage state.

The standard play is **isolate + summarize**: extract the offending computation into its
own internal function, then summarize that internal function in the spec. Summaries
replace the prover's "compute this exactly" requirement with "trust this property
holds." Internal-function isolation keeps the summary local — it doesn't affect anything
outside that one operation. Use the working-spec flow for the summary.

When you need to record auxiliary information that helps verification but isn't part of
the contract's domain logic, transient storage is a reasonable place to put it. Gas costs
are not your concern; pass the verifier first.

### `SANITY_FAILED` — rule passes vacuously

The rule's preconditions are unsatisfiable, so the assertion is unreachable and the rule
trivially passes. This counts as a **failure**, not a success.

Common causes:
- The rule's `require`s conflict with the implementation's invariants or `require`s.
- The function under test always reverts (implementation bug).
- A rule assumption ("this function does not revert") is wrong because of the current
  implementation.

Find the contradiction and fix whichever side is wrong.

## Step 4 — Run the requirements judge

Once all specs verify, the requirements judge oracle evaluates each natural-language
requirement against your implementation. Each must be SATISFIED or LIKELY. If any are
REJECTED, address the failure and re-run both the prover and the judge — code changes
to satisfy a requirement may invalidate spec stamps.

## Step 5 — Deliver

Deliver via the `result` tool when:
- Every registered spec has been stamped via its own
  `certora_prover(target_spec=...)` run on the current code state.
- Every requirement is judged SATISFIED or LIKELY.
- Memory has been updated with your final approach summary.

## Working with the spec — when and how

You may NOT modify registered spec files via `put_file`. Specs are mutated via two paths
depending on intent:

### When the spec needs a *summary* (verification tractability)

Use the **working-spec flow**. Adding summaries doesn't change what the spec proves; it
gives the prover the help it needs to prove it. This is the right path for HAVOC
mitigation, timeout remediation, and isolating non-linear math.

```
write_working_spec(new_cvl=<full updated spec text>)
  → certora_prover(use_working_spec=True, ...)        # iterate; does NOT stamp
  → write_working_spec(...)                            # refine
  → ... (as many cycles as needed)
  → commit_working_spec(target_path=<spec VFS path>, explanation=...)
  → certora_prover(target_spec=<same path>, use_working_spec=False)   # stamp
```

There's only one working-spec slot — it's a scratch file, not bound to any particular
spec until commit. Working-spec runs do NOT stamp; only post-commit
`certora_prover(target_spec=...)` runs stamp the spec as VERIFIED for delivery.

### When the spec is *wrong* (corrections)

Use `propose_spec_change(target_path=..., proposed_spec=...)`. The user reviews. Only for
changes that prove the same property in a different way — never weakening.

## CVL questions — use the researcher

For CVL syntax, patterns, language features, summary idioms, or any "how do I express X
in CVL?" question — delegate to the **`cvl_research`** sub-agent. It synthesizes answers
from the manual and knowledge base across multiple steps, which produces a far more
complete answer than a single manual search.

The researcher only knows CVL — it has no view of your VFS, the spec files, or the system
doc. For *source-code* questions ("what does this contract do?", "where is X defined?",
"what's already in the implementation?") use the VFS tools (`get_file`, `grep_files`,
`list_files`) instead. Phrase researcher questions self-contained — include the CVL
fragment or pattern you're asking about, since the sub-agent can't see your state.

Use `cvl_manual_search` only for narrow lookups where you already know the section name
or want to skim near-hits.

Do NOT invent CVL syntax based on guesses. If you're not sure something is valid CVL, ask
the researcher first.

## Code style for verifiability

The high-level frame: **prover incompleteness manifests as timeouts; the antidote is
isolation + summarization.** Write code so the awkward parts have a natural seam where a
summary can attach.

Specific patterns to lean on:

- **Non-linear math, bitwise tricks, custom packing** → extract into internal functions
  so they can be summarized in CVL. Internal functions are NEVER `envfree` and a summary
  on them is local to that operation.
- **Mirrored storage / heavy in-memory caching** → don't. Read directly from storage.
  The prover handles direct storage access well; mirrored caches need extra invariants
  the prover has to discharge.
- **Public storage fields** → only mark `public` when you actually need the
  auto-generated getter. Direct storage access in specs works on private fields too, and
  the synthesised getters frequently cause stack-too-deep errors.
- **Gas / efficiency optimizations** → secondary to verification. Inefficient code that
  verifies beats efficient code that times out.

